estershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Corse, Gloucestershire, England":"Corse, Gloucestershire, England","Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Toddington, Gloucestershire, England":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"1247–21 May 1281":"1247–21 May 1281","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1272–1336":"1272–1336","1275–1308":"1275–1308","1275–Male":"1275–Deceased","1247–1281":"1247–1281","21 May 1281":"21 May 1281","1275":"1275","1272":"1272","1271":"1271","1281":"1281","1291":"1291","1259":"1259","1336":"1336","1247":"1247","ABT 1275":"about 1275","1245":"1245","about 1275":"about 1275","1308":"1308","Toddington, Tewkesbury Borough, Gloucestershire, England":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Corse, Gloucestershire, England":"Corse, Gloucestershire, England","Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Toddington, Gloucestershire, England":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Swine","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Swinn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Swinn","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Swine (ER Yorks).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>swin(ne)</i> ‘swine, pig’ (Old English  <i>swīn</i>), for a swineherd (  see  Swinerd  ) or for someone who resembled a pig in some way. Some early bearers may belong with (1)."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":12,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Marie de la Swine was born in 1247, in Corse, Gloucestershire, England. She married John de Tracy in 1271, in Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died on 21 May 1281, in Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, at the age of 34, and was buried in Toddington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1247–21 May 1281":"1247–21. mai 1281","1245–1291":"1245–1291","1272–1336":"1272–1336","1275–1308":"1275–1308","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1247–1281":"1247–1281","21 May 1281":"21. mai 1281","1275":"1275","1272":"1272","1271":"1271","1281":"1281","1291":"1291","1259":"1259","1336":"1336","1247":"1247","ABT 1275":"umbes 1275","1245":"1245","about 1275":"umbes 1275","1308":"1308","Toddington, Tewkesbury Borough, Gloucestershire, England":"Toddington, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Corse, Gloucestershire, England":"Corse, Gloucestershire, England","Toddington, Glouces